<span id="freeTextContainer15958343163773111042">I am glad I had marked this book to revisit. Sometimes it happens like that when one is not in a receptive mood for a particular kind of book. I found this second try at it very rewarding. It goes back to the late 1980&apos;s in Belfast region and features a policeman who is dogged in his approach to solve murders and is decidedly self directed even when not supported by those in charge, following his beliefs at all costs.<br/>I had some challenges reading the format available from my library and this is </span>
  <span id="freeText15958343163773111042" style="display:none">I am glad I had marked this book to revisit. Sometimes it happens like that when one is not in a receptive mood for a particular kind of book. I found this second try at it very rewarding. It goes back to the late 1980's in Belfast region and features a policeman who is dogged in his approach to solve murders and is decidedly self directed even when not supported by those in charge, following his beliefs at all costs.<br />I had some challenges reading the format available from my library and this is the only one of the Sean Duffy series they have - so I will go in search to ensure I am able to read all of the Sean Duffy books. It's good stuff!<br />Factoids: he is Catholic, though only child, living and working in Protestant territory; Thatcher is around; riots are the norm; prisoners go on hunger strikes; homosexual acts are against the law and play a part in the action; there are a whole lot of guns on all sides; police must check for mercury bombs every time they enter their cars... and multiple threats do result in serious injury to Sean. <br />Looking forward to next book in series!</span>
